of Capital Creation</h1><h1 style="margin-top: 0px;"><p style="font-size: 11px; font-weight: 400;">The easiest way to understand the functional creation and control of capital is in terms of 'geological' layers. The Production Layer, at the bottom, does not require the other layers in order to operate as a market driven economy. However, on its own it cannot compete with a capital geology. Whilst individual businesses are rendered less competitive from capital extraction, as long as the resource is transferred to promising supply chains via capital investment, businesses inside the same The process of capitalisation was known and documented perfectly at the time by economists and political thinkers. Once up and running, it becomes a vicious circle: the more land that can be territorialised by a landlord, the greater the rents to extract, increasing private wealth and hence political power. Power adds rights to own that bequeaths additional territory and so on. The dividing line is not so much wealth, but rights, where rights to consume are a consequence of the arrangement.</span></p>" vertex="1"> <mxGeometry height="140" width="740" x="40" y="430"
